canonical:
  title: 告哀表
  author: 崔惟淸
  language: lzh
  text: 臣諱言私門積釁臣父先臣諱遘疾彌留於今月二十八日奄辭聖代臣諱誠哀誠切頓首頓首伏念臣諱自緣薄祐遽失嚴顔五內崩摧呼天叩地瞻望宸闕禮謹告終臣無任攀慕號絶之至謹差使朝議大夫尙書禮部侍郞輕車都尉賜紫金魚袋李之茂奉表訃奏以聞
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 告哀表
  author: 崔惟淸
  language: lzh
  text: 臣諱言。私門積釁。臣父先臣諱遘疾彌留。於今月二十八日。奄辭聖代。臣諱誠哀誠切。頓首頓首。伏念臣諱。自緣薄祐。遽失嚴顔。五內崩摧。呼天叩地。瞻望宸闕。禮謹告終。臣無任攀慕號絶之至。謹差使朝議大夫尙書禮部侍郞輕車都尉賜紫金魚袋李之茂。奉表訃奏以聞。
korean:
  title: 상을 당한 것을 알리는 글
  author: 최유청
  language: kor
  text: 신 휘(諱)는 아롭니다.사문(私門)에 죄가 쌓이어 신의 아버지 선신(先臣) 휘(諱)가 오랫동안 신병으로 고생하다가, 금월 28일에 그만 성대(聖代)를 하직하였으니, 신휘가 진실로 애통하고 진실로 애절하여, 머리를 조아리고 머리를 조아립니다.엎드려 생각하건대, 신 휘가 복이 없어서 갑자기 엄안(嚴顔)을 잃으니, 오장(五臟)이 무너지어 하늘을 부르고 땅을 두드리며, 대궐을 바라보고 고종(告終 부고(計告))의 예(禮)를 삼가 차립니다.신이 사모하고 울부짖는 지극한 설움을 가눌 길이 없사어, 삼가 조의대부상서예부시랑경거도위사자금어대(朝議大夫尙書禮部侍郞輕車都尉賜紫金魚袋) 이지무(李之茂)를 보내어 표를 받들어 부고(訃告)를 아룁니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0420_010_0070&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Upon Bereavement
  author: Choi Yujeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant grieves to speak. My humble household has long borne misfortune. My father, the late minister, suffered prolonged illness and on the twenty-eighth day of this month, he departed from this world. My sorrow knows no measure, my anguish cuts deepest. I bow my head again and again.

    I reflect upon my own meager fortune—to lose my father so suddenly leaves my heart torn asunder. The five organs within me crumble and fall. I cry out to Heaven and strike the earth. Though I gaze toward the palace, I can only observe the proper rites of mourning.

    I am overwhelmed by longing and grief beyond all bearing. Therefore I humbly send my messenger, the Court Counselor and Minister of Rites, bearing this memorial of notification that the court may be informed.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal notification of death (訃告), a genre of official correspondence in classical East Asian bureaucracy, structured with expressions of filial piety and submission to the throne.
    - The 'five organs' (五臟) is a reference to the classical understanding of the heart, liver, spleen, lungs, and kidneys as the seat of human emotion and vitality—here representing the author's complete emotional devastation.
    - The reference to losing 'grave countenance' (嚴顔) suggests not merely the loss of the father's physical form, but the loss of his dignity, authority, and moral presence.
